author: @stephens3909
text: setUp and tearDown aren't offensive but to add to this tutorial, you really shouldn't be making unit tests DRY or bringing in abstraction to testing otherwise it's "Yo dawg, I heard you liked tests, so I brought some tests for your tests for your tests."  Unit test cases should be mostly independent without relying on abstraction, repetitive and only care about what they are testing and nothing else. It's also great if you can share a full test case to a colleague and they are able to see clearly what is being tested, without them having to track back a bunch of other stuff just to understand.

author: @TheInimicus
text: 23:13 Don't do that! Don't move test logic/given to setUp(). Yea, it might be shorter, and that might "feel" as if this method was created for it, but please don't do that. That creates coupling between tests (so the tests can influence each other, they can pass when run together and fail when run separately, they can silence bugs, etc.), and it introduces shared state. If you want to lower the duplication, please use a private method and create the test fixtures each time for each test (not once in SetUp, and re-use it).

author: @garybloomlaw
text: Fantastic videos. I would add that the test cases can be spread across multiple classes. This allows you to group tests together so that you can make good use of setUp() and setUpClass().  For example, if you have multiple tests that require a database, you could group all those tests into a single class and have the setUpClass() method prepare the db.  Tests that don't involve the db would go into other test classes.  The larger the overall project, the more test classes you are likely to have.

author: @BabyBalla3score
text: What's the point of unit testing? I've seen articles saying it's to test the smallest units of code possible and make sure they run as intended but what if you already have a good idea of what exceptions to handle and when to handle them. Say you are making a medium sized script (like a few hundred lines) with a bunch of functions that are passed arguments that can be quite different at times. Is it possible to test functions that rely on input(arguments to be set) from other functions or functions that are called within other functions? Also, for smaller things like scripts, wouldn't it be fine to just make exceptions for the code at first and add more if need be? If you don't know what to expect when first writing the code and end up encountering something that throws an error then you probably wouldn't have accounted for that in a test either. What's the difference if the script is failing or if the test case is failing? As I write this, I am now thinking of the assert statement and how heavily used it is in testing. If you develop with some of these assertion rules in mind like param1 for foo(param1, param2) must be an int then why would you need to go write a unit test for it?  Sorry for the long question. I have a hard time seeing why this would be useful. Especially if you run a script a few times and clear any issues that you didn't account for at first.  Why go write a unit test after that?
